  title="Best Firewood for Melbourne Winters (and What NOT to Burn)"
  description="The wood you burn directly affects how fast your chimney gets dirty. Here's what Melbourne homeowners should be burning — and what you should never put in your fireplace."
  publishDate="April 2026"
  readTime="5 min"
>
  <p>The type of wood you burn has a bigger impact on your chimney than most people realise. Burn the right stuff and your chimney stays cleaner for longer. Burn the wrong stuff and you'll be fast-tracking creosote buildup and potentially damaging your flue. Here's the rundown for Melbourne households.</p>

  <h2>The Golden Rule: Burn Seasoned Hardwood</h2>

  <p>If there's one thing to take away from this article, it's this: <strong>only burn well-seasoned hardwood</strong>. Seasoned means properly dried — wood that has been split and stored with airflow for at least 12 months, ideally 18–24 months.</p>

  <p>Unseasoned or "green" wood contains high amounts of moisture. When it burns, instead of producing heat efficiently, a large portion of the energy goes into evaporating that water. The result is a cooler, smokier fire that produces significantly more creosote. It's worse for your chimney, worse for your air quality, and worse for your heating bill.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>A quick test for seasoned wood: well-dried hardwood will have cracks at the ends of the log, feel noticeably lighter than green wood, and make a sharp "crack" when two pieces are knocked together rather than a dull thud.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Best Firewood Species for Melbourne</h2>

  <h3>Red Gum (Eucalyptus camaldulensis)</h3>
  <p>Red gum is the gold standard for Melbourne firewood. It's dense, burns hot and long, produces good coals, and is widely available across Victoria. Well-seasoned red gum will heat your home efficiently and won't create excessive creosote. It does take longer to season than softer woods — 18 months is ideal — so make sure what you're buying is genuinely dry.</p>

  <h3>Ironbark</h3>
  <p>Even denser than red gum, ironbark burns exceptionally hot and holds a fire through the night better than almost any other species. It's harder to find and often more expensive, but if you can get it, it's excellent for a slow combustion heater. Burns clean and leaves minimal ash.</p>

  <h3>Box Species (Grey Box, Yellow Box)</h3>
  <p>Box eucalypts are another solid choice — hardwood, good heat output, readily available in Victoria. They season a bit more quickly than red gum and are a good all-round option for open fireplaces and wood heaters.</p>

  <h3>Stringybark</h3>
  <p>Burns well and is common in Victoria. A good mid-range option — not quite as dense as red gum or ironbark but performs well when properly seasoned. Good value when buying in larger quantities.</p>

  <h2>What NOT to Burn</h2>

  <h3>Green or Unseasoned Wood</h3>
  <p>As covered above — this is the biggest cause of avoidable creosote buildup. If your firewood hisses, steams, or is difficult to keep alight, it's too wet. Don't burn it.</p>

  <h3>Pine and Softwoods</h3>
  <p>Pine is sometimes sold as firewood and it lights easily — which is about the only thing in its favour. Softwoods burn fast, produce relatively little heat, and create significantly more creosote and flammable resin deposits than hardwoods. Pine is fine as kindling but shouldn't be your main fuel.</p>

  <h3>Treated Timber, Plywood, MDF</h3>
  <p>Never burn treated timber, plywood, MDF, painted wood or any manufactured board product. These contain adhesives, preservatives and chemical treatments that release toxic fumes when burned — not good for your family, and corrosive to your flue.</p>

  <h3>Wet Pallets</h3>
  <p>Pallet wood is tempting because it's free, but most pallets are made from softwood and may be treated with methyl bromide or other chemicals. If you use pallet wood, make sure it's heat-treated (stamped "HT"), untreated, and properly dried before burning.</p>

  <h3>Household Rubbish and Cardboard</h3>
  <p>Cardboard burns fast and hot in short bursts, which sounds useful for getting a fire going but actually causes temperature spikes that can crack flue tiles and increase creosote formation. Burning rubbish releases all kinds of chemicals into your home and chimney. Don't do it.</p>

